{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489171"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:07:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:07:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"609"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/609"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.11,0.37,0.45,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102802"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/609"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85286"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"478"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36162"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42111"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102802"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever and pleuritic chest pain. He is normally in good health, but did have a myocardial infarction five weeks ago. He has a medical history of retrosternal goitre with known tracheal deviation on previous imaging studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his respiratory rate is 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 85/min and temperature 37.2\u00baC. His chest is clear. His heart sounds muffled. His JVP is not raised. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous antibiotics","Loop or thiazide diuretic","A nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory agent","Urgent pericardiocentesis","Inotrope support"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is post-infarction pericarditis with a pericardial effusion, suggested by the enlarged cardiac silhouette, recent infarction and pleuritic pain. The initial treatment is a \u003Cstrong\u003Enonsteroidal anti-inflammatory agent\u003C/strong\u003E to control pain and inflammation. Guidelines now advocate concurrent low-dose colchicine to reduce recurrence and a proton pump inhibitor because people over 65 years are at higher risk of gastrointestinal harm from nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory agents; clinicians should use the lowest effective dose for the shortest necessary duration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn urgent echocardiogram should be performed to assess the size and extent of the pericardial effusion. If the effusion is large and causing haemodynamic instability, then a \u003Cstrong\u003Epericardiocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered. However, in this stable patient, immediate pericardiocentesis is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence of cardiac tamponade, as indicated by the normal pulse pressure and the absence of elevated JVP. The patient is not in cardiogenic shock, as he does not exhibit symptoms such as shortness of breath, tachycardia, or decreased consciousness, so \u003Cstrong\u003Einotrope support\u003C/strong\u003E is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated, as there is no sign of a bacterial aetiology for this effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiuretics\u003C/strong\u003E would be used for effusions caused by fluid overload, such as in heart failure, but are not appropriate in this case of post-infarction pericarditis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a stable patient with post-infarction pericarditis, the first action should be to provide pain relief with a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory agent.","Post-infarction pericarditis can occur days to weeks after a myocardial infarction and is characterised by pleuritic chest pain and fever."],"references":["Rahman A, Saraswat A. Pericarditis. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2017;46:810-4. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/november/pericarditis","Sagrist\u00e0-Sauleda J, Merc\u00e9 AS, Soler-Soler J. Diagnosis and management of pericardial effusion. World J Cardiol. 2011 May 26;3(5):135-43. doi: 10.4330/wjc.v3.i5.135. PMID: 21666814; PMCID: PMC3110902. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21666814/","Imazio M, Adler Y. Management of pericardial effusion. Eur Heart J. 2013 Apr;34(16):1186-97. doi: 10.1093/eurheartj/ehs372. Epub 2012 Nov 2. PMID: 23125278. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23125278/","Leib AD, Foris LA, Nguyen T, et al. Dressler Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441988/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"609"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19771"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19771"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4675b326-c029-47fc-a360-b286a5a26871.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4675b326-c029-47fc-a360-b286a5a26871.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":537,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85286"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-16T08:27:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-16T08:27:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"609"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102802"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite